#X text 35 17 In this example we combine keyboard tracking \, envelope and LFO as modulation sources. We now use [keytrack~] for simplicity and we combine its ratio output by multiplying it to the other modulation sources (all with independent modulation amount. The envelope and LFO amount are set in cents and converted to ratio. We're combining 2 detuned oscilators and using [moog~] with its internal drive parameter. This structure is a decent basic subtractive synth. In the end we add some reverb. Of course \, many subtractive synths also incorporate many effects like flanging \, delay \, reverb \, etc..., f 83;
#X text 374 533 HINT: We've had an example earlier before where we used keyboard tracking to set a ratio multiplier for the envelopes. You can expand on this idea and also have the keyboard tracking affect the the envelope time for the filter and/or amplitude. Not only that \, but you can also think of having the LFO speed higher for higher pitches! Do it as an excercize!, f 34;
